<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-06-11</title>

<p>This run uncovered three converging threads in embodied AI and long-horizon reasoning. World models are maturing from standalone predictors into policy infrastructure—steering VLAs with frozen priors (World Pilot) and training faster via multi-horizon supervision (Next Forcing). Embodied-R1.5 tests the bold hypothesis that a reasoning-first foundation model can substitute for massive action pretraining when adapted downstream. And ALE-Bench opens a new evaluation frontier where pass/fail saturation gives way to open-ended score optimization, revealing that even frontier LLMs remain far from expert-level consistency in algorithm engineering.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> Next Forcing is the clearest seed for a general training-recipe improvement. Its multi-chunk prediction objective cures a real pathology—myopic supervision via appearance shortcuts—in autoregressive video world models, yielding 2.3× faster convergence and SOTA results on RoboTwin. The mechanism is composable with existing context-construction and noise-scheduling methods, and the inference-speedup side effect is nearly free.</p>
</callout>

<h1>World Models as Embodied Infrastructure</h1>

<p>Two papers this week treat world models not as end-to-end policy generators, but as modular infrastructure: one steers an existing VLA with frozen world-model priors, the other improves world-model training itself. Together they suggest a shift from "bigger world models" to "smarter ways to build and use them."</p>

