<h2>Next Forcing: Causal World Modeling with Multi-Chunk Prediction</h2>
<p>Gangwei Xu et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.11187">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.11187">PDF</a></p>

<p>Next Forcing addresses a training pathology in autoregressive video world models that the authors call <b>myopic supervision</b>. In standard teacher forcing, the model denoises the current chunk conditioned on clean past chunks. At high frame rates (e.g. 50 fps), adjacent chunks are visually almost identical. The denoising task therefore admits a powerful <em>appearance shortcut</em>: the model can drive most of the loss down by learning a near-identity map from the clean past chunk to the current one, adding only tiny residual corrections. This shortcut is much easier to fit than the underlying physical dynamics, and it absorbs a large share of the gradient signal.</p>

<p>The cure is <b>multi-chunk prediction (MCP)</b>. Next Forcing bolts three lightweight auxiliary modules onto a 30-layer Wan2.2 Transformer backbone. Each module predicts a video chunk at a future horizon—next¹, next², next³—simultaneously with the main model's current-chunk prediction. The key is not just "predict more chunks," but the specific design choices that force the <em>main backbone</em> to learn:</p>

<ul>
  <li><b>Multi-layer feature fusion</b> (layers {4, 12, 20, 30}): MCP modules consume intermediate hidden states, not just the final layer. Without this (−2.2 points), the MCP loss is solved by the lightweight heads alone and the backbone receives weak gradients.</li>
  <li><b>Higher timestep shift</b> (<latex>s_{\text{mcp}} = 10</latex> vs. <latex>s_{\text{main}} = 5</latex>): A larger shift pushes noise mass toward higher noise levels. At higher noise, the MCP input carries almost no information about its own target, so the module is forced to rely on the main model's representations. Ablating <latex>s_{\text{mcp}}</latex> down to 5 drops performance by 2.6 points—this is the secret sauce.</li>
  <li><b>Causal chain across depths</b>: Each depth builds on the previous depth's hidden state, so near-future predictions inform farther-future ones.</li>
</ul>

<p>The training objective combines main losses and MCP losses:</p>

<p><latex>\mathcal{L} = \mathcal{L}_{\text{video}} + \mathcal{L}_{\text{action}} + \sum_{k=1}^{3} w_k \cdot \mathcal{L}_k^{\text{MCP}}</latex></p>

<p>At inference, the MCP modules can either be discarded entirely (zero-overhead mode—all quality gains come from the enriched training signal baked into the backbone) or retained for parallel chunk generation (2× speedup, since depth-1 MCP predicts the next chunk alongside the current one).</p>

<p>The results are strong and frame-rate-dependent. At 12 fps the gap is modest (~1–2 points at convergence), because the appearance shortcut is weaker. At 50 fps the gap becomes a chasm: Next Forcing is +24.7 / +29.7 points ahead at 5k steps, and matches LingBot-VA's 45k-step accuracy at only 20k steps—a <b>2.3× convergence speedup</b>. Final SOTA on RoboTwin is 94.1% / 93.5% (Clean / Random).</p>

<p><b>Non-obvious finding:</b> Lighter MCP heads actually score <em>higher</em> (1 transformer block: 86.5% vs. 3 blocks: 85.8%), but the paper sticks with 3 blocks because 1 block produces visual artifacts in the MCP-generated chunks—important for the parallel inference mode. This reveals a tension: training wants the heads weak (so the main model must work), but inference wants them strong enough to produce clean chunks.</p>

<p><b>Non-obvious finding:</b> The gains generalize far beyond robotics. On general video pretraining (3.5M in-house clips), Next Forcing reduces FVD by &gt;50% and surpasses the baseline at 10k steps vs. 50k. Myopic supervision is not a robotics-specific pathology—it afflicts any autoregressive video model trained with single-chunk teacher forcing.</p>

<p><b>Honest limitation:</b> The GitHub repo is only a project page; the training code is not public. The reproduction barrier is high. Our PyTorch sketch (preserved in the thread) fills part of this gap but is not a full training pipeline.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:nextforcing:training-curves]]</p>

<h1>Unified Embodied Intelligence</h1>

<p>Embodied-R1.5 asks a high-stakes question: can a single 8B VLM, trained on diverse embodied reasoning tasks, internalize enough physical understanding that downstream VLA training requires only a small amount of action data?</p>

<h2>Embodied-R1.5: Evolving Physical Intelligence via Embodied Foundation Models</h2>
<p>Yifu Yuan et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.11324">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.11324">PDF</a></p>

<p>Embodied-R1.5 organizes embodied intelligence into three progressive dimensions: <b>Cognition &amp; Spatial Reasoning</b> (perceive and understand), <b>Planning &amp; Correction</b> (schedule and recover), and <b>Pointing &amp; Location</b> (ground reasoning in coordinates and trajectories). The bet is that unifying these in a single model allows information to flow freely across dimensions without external communication.</p>

<p>The model achieves SOTA on 16 of 24 embodied VLM benchmarks, with an average of 70.4% across 21 main accuracy-based benchmarks—surpassing Gemini-Robotics-ER-1.5 by 17.0% and GPT-5.4 by 21.7%. More critically, when adapted into a VLA with only a small action dataset, it outperforms π₀.₅ across 4 manipulation benchmark suites: 92.4% on SimplerEnv (vs. π₀.₅'s 72.7%) and strong gains on LIBERO and PartNet-Mobility.</p>

<p><b>The data system is the real engine.</b> Three automated pipelines construct a 15B-token corpus:</p>

<ol>
  <li><b>3D Scene Annotation</b> (~20K samples): An 8-step pipeline (resize → tag → geometry → segment → 3D lift → normal estimation → world-frame alignment → QA generation) produces tabletop spatial-reasoning data from single RGB images. The code for this pipeline is fully released and well-engineered, with quality controls at every stage.</li>
  <li><b>Failure-Aware Correction</b> (~800K samples): Structured perturbations of correct plans and executions generate detection → localization → correction QA triples. The logic is described in detail but <b>the generation code is absent</b> from the repo.</li>
  <li><b>Functional Affordance &amp; Trajectory</b>: Simulation renders and hand-object interaction data scale part-level grounding and visual trace generation. Again, the extraction code is not present.</li>
</ol>

<p><b>The most important code discovery:</b> The RL stage uses <b>MBPO</b>, not GRPO. The advantage estimator normalizes by <code>scores.std()</code> over the <em>entire mixed batch</em>, not per-group:</p>

<pre lang="python" caption="MBPO advantage estimator from core_algos.py"><code>@register_adv_estimator(AdvantageEstimator.MBPO)
def compute_mbpo_outcome_advantage(token_level_rewards, response_mask, index, eps=1e-6):
    scores = token_level_rewards.sum(dim=-1)
    id2score = defaultdict(list)
    id2mean = {}
    for i in range(bsz):
        id2score[index[i]].append(scores[i])
    for idx in id2score:
        id2mean[idx] = torch.mean(torch.stack(id2score[idx]))
    batch_std = scores.std()          # ← entire mixed batch
    for i in range(bsz):
        scores[i] = (scores[i] - id2mean[index[i]]) / (batch_std + eps)
    returns = scores.unsqueeze(-1) * response_mask
    return returns, returns</code></pre>

<p>This is elegant: it preserves intra-group relative ordering while unifying gradient magnitudes across heterogeneous tasks. It requires no task labels, no EMA history, and no per-task statistics. Our probe demonstrates that on a toy mixed batch, GRPO blows up tiny-variance tasks into ±1.0 advantages while compressing high-variance tasks, whereas MBPO gives both tasks stable, proportionate updates.</p>

<p><b>The biggest gap between paper and code:</b> The Planner-Grounder-Corrector (PGC) closed-loop framework—described as enabling autonomous planning, execution, and self-correction on long-horizon tasks—is <b>not implemented</b> in the released code. Only a basic 3-round planning→reflection demo exists in <code>inference/reflection.py</code>. The milk-tea and cup-stacking demos are impressive, but researchers cannot reproduce them from the repository alone.</p>

<p><b>Another inconsistency:</b> The paper states the vision encoder is jointly trained in SFT, but the SFT config sets <code>freeze_vision_tower: true</code>. Only the RFT config unfreezes it. This suggests either the released SFT config is not the exact one used, or the paper's statement applies only to RFT.</p>

<p><b>A deeper finding on "reasoning":</b> The paper claims in §4.2.1 that the model learns "adaptive thinking"—allocating reasoning tokens on demand—because RL "only constrains the output format without forcing explicit reasoning chains." But the training code in <code>EasyR1/verl/utils/dataset.py</code> hardcodes into every prompt: <em>"You FIRST think about the reasoning process as an internal monologue and then provide the final answer."</em> This is not emergent behavior; it is explicit prompt injection. Worse, <code>embodied_reward.py</code> strips everything outside <code>&lt;answer&gt;</code> tags and scores only the final answer. The RL objective is structurally incapable of teaching reasoning quality—it can only select for answers that happen to be correct, regardless of whether the reasoning chain makes sense. The "System 2 / System 1" dual-system framing is likewise a metaphor, not an architecture: the action head generates continuous actions from VLM hidden states, not by parsing explicit reasoning tokens. There is no ablation showing that removing reasoning text hurts VLA performance. Until such evidence appears, "reasoning" in Embodied-R1.5 should be read as pattern-matched text generation that correlates with correct answers—impressive in breadth, but not evidence of genuine cognitive computation allocation.</p>

<p><b>Honest assessment:</b> Embodied-R1.5 is a high-quality, ambitious piece of work whose empirical contributions (benchmark results, data engineering, MBPO normalization) are genuine and valuable. But its "reasoning" framing oversells what the experiments validate. The paper measures benchmark accuracy, not reasoning quality. The core claim—that unified embodied capabilities internalized in a VLM can reduce downstream VLA data requirements—is well-supported. The gaps (PGC framework unreleased, two data pipelines absent, reasoning claims unsupported by training code) are significant but do not undermine the reproducible benchmark results.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:embodiedr1:capability-taxonomy]]</p>

<h1>Beyond Pass/Fail: Benchmarking Long-Horizon Algorithm Engineering</h1>

<p>While embodied AI papers chase simulation metrics, ALE-Bench quietly opens a harder frontier: can an AI system do what skilled human programmers do over weeks—iteratively refine an algorithm for an NP-hard optimization problem with no known exact solution?</p>

<h2>ALE-Bench: A Benchmark for Long-Horizon Objective-Driven Algorithm Engineering</h2>
<p>Yuki Imajuku et al. (2025) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2506.09050">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2506.09050">PDF</a></p>

<p>ALE-Bench is the first large-scale benchmark for <b>score-based algorithmic programming contests</b>—specifically the AtCoder Heuristic Contest (AHC). It ships with 40 real contest problems (routing, scheduling, planning, power-grid balancing), official scorers, visualizers, human leaderboards, and a Python framework that replicates the contest environment in Docker.</p>

<p>The key metric is <b>performance</b>—an Elo-like score derived from rank within the original contest leaderboard. Unlike pass/fail benchmarks, AHC problems are open-ended: even after AI surpasses the best humans, scores can keep improving.</p>

<p><b>Frontier LLM performance is competent but inconsistent.</b> In one-shot mode, o3-high is the only model to break average performance 1000 (1044). Most models cluster between 550–850. With 4 hours of iterative refinement, o4-mini-high reaches 1520 average performance and a rating of 2104—top 11.8% of humans. But <b>rating overestimates AI skill</b>: humans in that rating band average 56.2% of problems ≥1600, while o4-mini-high achieves only 32.5%, closer to the 1600–1700 human band.</p>

<p>LLMs show <b>high variance</b>: they spike to ≥2400 on 5% of problems but crater on others. They also outperform humans more on short contests than long ones, because they can generate 100–1000 solution variants in hours—impossible for humans. The "parallel search" effect flatters short-contest performance, while long contests (where humans develop deep, problem-specific insights) remain harder.</p>

<p><b>The critical claim:</b> Is the iterative refinement "genuine long-horizon problem solving" or just "massively parallel search of mediocre ideas"? The paper addresses this with a targeted experiment: on 6 problems where o4-mini-high achieved ≥2000, 150 independent one-shot trials were run (matching the ~150 generations in iterative refinement). The peak scores from independent search were consistently 300–800 points below iterative-refinement peaks:</p>

